# nl-rag distilled facts ‚Äî domain: flexbox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] One of the reasons flexbox is so useful is that it enables proper alignment, including providing a quick method of vertically centering elements.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this guide, we will take a thorough look at how the alignment and justification properties work in flexbox.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Flexbox provides several properties to control alignment and spacing, with `align-items` and `justify-content` being fundamental for centering elements.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] To center an element, we use the `align-items` property to align the item on the cross axis, which in this case is the block axis running vertically.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] We use `justify-content` to align the item on the main axis, which in this case is the inline axis running horizontally.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Change the size of the container or nested element in the code example below.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The nested element always remains centered.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The properties we will look at in this guide are as follows.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] We will also discover how auto margins can be used for alignment in flexbox.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `align-items` property, set on the flex container, and the `align-self` property, set on flex items, control the alignment of flex items on the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The cross axis runs down the columns if `flex-direction` is `row` and along the rows if `flex-direction` is `column`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this basic flex example, we're using cross-axis alignment.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] When we add `display: flex` to a container, the child items become flex items arranged in a row.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] By default, they will all stretch to match the height of the tallest item, as that item defines the height of the items on the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If the flex container has a height set, the items will stretch to that height, regardless of how much content is in each item.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The reason the items become the same height is that the initial value of `align-items`, the property that controls alignment on the cross axis, is set to `stretch`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In the example below, the value of `align-items` is `stretch`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Try the other values and see how the items align against each other in the flex container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `align-items` property sets the `align-self` property on all of the flex items as a group.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] This means you can explicitly declare the `align-self` property to target a single item.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `align-self` property accepts all of the same values as `align-items`, plus a value of `auto`, which resets the value to that defined on the flex container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this next live example, the flex container has `align-items: flex-start`, which means the items are all aligned to the start of the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Using the `first-child` selector, the first item is set to `align-self: stretch`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Another item with the `selected` class has `align-self: center` set.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Change the value of `align-items` or change the values of `align-self` on the individual items to see how this works.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Thus far, we have looked at alignment behavior when the `flex-direction` defaults to `row` while working in a language written top to bottom, with a horizontal main axis and vertical cross axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] (Three items, the first aligned to flex-start, second to center, third to flex-end.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Keeping the same writing mode, when the `flex-direction` is changed to `column`, the `align-items` and `align-self` properties will align the items to the left and right instead of top and bottom; these properties are still aligning items along the cross axis, but the cross axis is now horizontal!
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] You can try this out in the example below, which has a flex container with `flex-direction: column` yet otherwise is exactly the same as the previous example.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] So far, we have focused on aligning items or individual items inside the area defined by a flex container containing a single line of flex items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] When flex items are allowed to wrap across multiple lines, the `align-content` property can be used to control the distribution of space between the lines, also known as **packing flex lines**.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] For `align-content` to have an effect, the cross axis dimension (the height in this case) of the flex container must be greater than needed to display the items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] It then works on all the items as a set.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `align-content` values dictate what happens with the extra available space and the alignment of the entire set of items within it.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In the live example below, the flex container has a height of `400 pixels`, which is more than needed to display our items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The value of `align-content` is `space-between`, which means that the available space is shared out *between* the flex lines, which are placed flush with the start and end of the container on the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Try out the other values to see how the `align-content` property works.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Once again we can switch our `flex-direction` to `column` in order to see how this property behaves when we are working by column.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] As before, we need enough space in the cross axis to have some free space after displaying all of the items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Now that we have seen how alignment works on the cross axis, we can take a look at the main axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Here we only have one property available to us ‚Äî `justify-content`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] This is because we are only dealing with items as a group on the main axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] With `justify-content` we control what happens with available space, should there be more space than is needed to display the items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In our initial example with `display: flex` on the container, the items display as a row and all line up at the start of the container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] This is due to the initial value of `justify-content` being `normal`, which behaves as `start`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Any available space is placed at the end of the items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] (Three items, each 100 pixels wide in a 500 pixel container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `baseline` values aren't relevant in this dimension.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Otherwise, the `justify-content` property accepts the same values as `align-content`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In the example below, the value of `justify-content` is `space-between`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The available space after displaying the items is distributed between the items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The left and right item line up flush with the start and end.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If the main axis is in the block direction because `flex-direction` is set to `column`, then `justify-content` will distribute space between items in that dimension as long as there is space in the flex container to distribute.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Remember that with all of these alignment methods, the values of `start` and `end` are writing mode-aware.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If the value of `justify-content` is `start` and the writing mode is left-to-right, as in English, the items will align starting at the left side of the container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] However if the writing mode is right-to-left as in Arabic, the items will line up starting at the right side of the container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The live example below has the `direction` property set to `rtl` to force a right-to-left flow for our items.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] You can remove this, or change the values of `justify-content` to see how flexbox behaves when the start of the inline direction is on the right.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The direction of `flex-start` of the line will also change if you change the `flex-direction` property ‚Äî for example, using `row-reverse` instead of `row`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The directions of `start` and `end` are unaffected by `flex-direction` changes.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this next example, `flex-direction: row-reverse` and `justify-content: flex-end` define the direction and location of the items within the flex container.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In a left to right language, the items line up on the left.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Try changing `flex-direction: row-reverse` to `flex-direction: row`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] You will see that the items now move to the right-hand side, and the visual order of the items is reversed.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] While this may all seem a little confusing, the rule to remember is that unless you do something to change it, flex items lay themselves out in the direction that words are laid out in the language of your document along the inline, row axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] `flex-start` will be where the beginning of a sentence of text would start.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] You can switch them to display in the block direction for the language of your document by selecting `flex-direction: column`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Then, `start` and `flex-start` will be where the top of your first paragraph of text would start.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If you change `flex-direction` to one of the reverse values, they will lay themselves out from the end axis and in the reverse order to the way words are written in the language of your document.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Then, `flex-start` will change to the end of that axis ‚Äî so to the location where your lines would wrap if working in rows, or at the end of your last paragraph of text in the block direction.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] We don't have a `justify-items` or `justify-self` property available to us on the main axis as our items are treated as a group on that axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] However it is possible to do some individual alignment in order to separate an item or a group of items from others by using auto margins along with flexbox.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] A common pattern is a navigation bar where some key items are aligned to the right, with the main group on the left.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] You might think that this should be a use case for a `justify-self` property.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] As an example, take the following image with three items on one side and two on the other.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If `justify-self` were to work on flex items and was set on item *d*, it would also change the alignment of item *e* that follows, which may or may not be what is intended.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Instead, the *d* item can be pushed over using CSS margins.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this live example, item 4 is separated from the first three items by setting `margin-left` to `auto`, which consumes all the space it can in its axis.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] This is how centering a block with `margin` auto left and right works.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Each side tries to take as much space as it can, and so the block is pushed into the middle.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] In this live example, the flex items are arranged in a row with the basic flex values, and the class `push`, set on the fourth item, applies `margin-left: auto` to that item.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] Try removing the class on the fourth item or adding the class to a different item to see how it works.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] To create a gap between flex items, use the `gap`, `column-gap`, and `row-gap` properties.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `column-gap` property creates gaps between items in a row.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `row-gap` property creates gaps between flex lines when you have `flex-wrap` set to `wrap`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The `gap` property is a shorthand that sets both `row-gap` and `column-gap`.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] The gaps between flex items or flex lines depend on the direction.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] If the `flex-direction` property creates rows, the first value defines the gap between flex lines, and the second value defines the gap between items within each line.
[src:flexbox/aligning-items-in-a-flex-container] With columns (when `flex-direction` is set to `column` or `column-reverse`), the first value defines the gap between flex items, and the second value defines the gaps between flex lines.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The flexible box layout module (usually referred to as flexbox) is a one-dimensional layout model for distributing space between items and includes numerous alignment capabilities.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This article gives an outline of the main features of flexbox, which we will explore in more detail in the rest of these guides.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When we describe flexbox as being one-dimensional we are describing the fact that flexbox deals with layout in one dimension at a time ‚Äî either as a row or as a column.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This can be contrasted with the two-dimensional model of CSS Grid Layout, which controls columns and rows together.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When working with flexbox you need to think in terms of two axes ‚Äî the *main axis* and the *cross axis*.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The main axis is defined by the `flex-direction` property, and the cross axis runs perpendicular to it.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Everything we do with flexbox refers back to these axes, so it is worth understanding how they work from the outset.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Should you choose `row` or `row-reverse`, your main axis will run along the row in the **inline direction**.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Choose `column` or `column-reverse` and your main axis will run in the **block direction**, from the top of the page to the bottom.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The cross axis runs perpendicular to the main axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Therefore, if your `flex-direction` (main axis) is set to `row` or `row-reverse` the cross axis runs down the columns.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If your main axis is `column` or `column-reverse` then the cross axis runs along the rows.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Another vital area of understanding is how flexbox makes no assumption about the writing mode of the document.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Flexbox doesn't just assume that all lines of text start at the top left of a document and run towards the right-hand side, with new lines appearing one under the other.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Rather, it supports all writing modes, like other logical properties and values.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can read more about the relationship between flexbox and writing modes in a later article; however, the following description should help explain why we do not talk about left and right and top and bottom when we describe the direction that our flex items flow in.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If the `flex-direction` is `row` and I am working in English, then the start edge of the main axis will be on the left, the end edge on the right.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If I were to work in Arabic, then the start edge of my main axis would be on the right and the end edge on the left.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In both cases the start edge of the cross-axis is at the top of the flex container and the end edge at the bottom, as both languages have a horizontal writing mode.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] After a while, thinking about start and end rather than left and right becomes natural, and will be useful to you when dealing with other layout methods such as CSS Grid Layout which follow the same patterns.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] An area of a document that is laid out using flexbox is called a **flex container**.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To create a flex container, set the area's `display` property to `flex`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] When we do this, the direct children of that container become **flex items**.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can explicitly control whether the container itself is displayed inline or in block formatting context using `inline flex` or `inline-flex` for inline flex containers or `block flex` or `flex` for block level flex containers.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The result of this is that your items will all line up in a row, using the size of the content as their size in the main axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If there are more items than can fit in the container, they will not wrap but will instead overflow.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If some items are taller than others, all items will stretch along the full length of the cross-axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can see in the live sample below how this looks.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Adding the `flex-direction` property to the flex container allows us to change the direction in which our flex items display.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Setting `flex-direction: row-reverse` will keep the items displaying along the row, however the start and end lines are switched.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we change `flex-direction` to `column` the main axis switches and our items now display in a column.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Set `column-reverse` and the start and end lines are again switched.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below has `flex-direction` set to `row-reverse`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try the other values ‚Äî `row`, `column` and `column-reverse` ‚Äî to see what happens to the content.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] While flexbox is a one dimensional model, it is possible to make flex items wrap across multiple lines.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you do this, you should consider each line as a new flex container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Any space distribution will happen across each line, without reference to the previous or subsequent lines.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To cause wrapping behavior add the property `flex-wrap` with a value of `wrap`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Now, if your items are too large to all display in one line, they will wrap onto another line.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below contains items that have been given a `width`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The total width of the items is too wide for the flex container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] As `flex-wrap` is set to `wrap`, the items wrap across multiple lines.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you set it to `nowrap`, which is the initial value, they will shrink to fit the container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] They shrink because they are using initial flexbox values, including `flex-shrink: 1`, that allows items to shrink.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `nowrap` would cause an overflow if the items were not able to shrink, or could not shrink small enough to fit.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Find out more about wrapping flex items in the guide Mastering wrapping of flex items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can combine the two properties `flex-direction` and `flex-wrap` into the `flex-flow` shorthand.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the live sample below, try changing the first value to one of the allowable values for `flex-direction` - `row`, `row-reverse`, `column` or `column-reverse`, and also change the second to `wrap` and `nowrap`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] We will take a brief look at these properties below, but if you want more comprehensive information, take a look at the Controlling ratios of flex items on the main axis guide.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Before we can make sense of these properties we need to consider the concept of **available space**.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] What we are doing when we change the value of these flex properties is to change the way that available space is distributed amongst our items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This concept of available space is also important when we come to look at aligning items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we have three 100 pixel-wide items in a container which is 500 pixels wide, then the space we need to lay out our items is 300 pixels.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This leaves 200 pixels of available space.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we don't change the initial values then flexbox will put that space after the last item.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we instead would like the items to grow and fill the space, then we need to have a method of distributing the leftover space between the items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex` properties that we apply to the items themselves, enable dictating how that available space should be distributed among the sibling flex items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex-basis` is what defines the size of that item in terms of the space it leaves as available space.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of this property is `auto` ‚Äî in this case the browser looks to see if the item has a size.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the example above, all of the items have a width of 100 pixels.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If the items don't have a size then the content's size is used as the flex-basis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This is why when we just declare `display: flex` on the parent to create flex items, the items all move into a row and take only as much space as they need to display their contents.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With the `flex-grow` property set to a positive integer, if there is available space, the flex item can grow along the main axis from its `flex-basis`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Whether the item stretches to take up all the available space on that axis, or just a portion of the available space depends on if the other items are allowed to grow too and the value of their `flex-grow` properties.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Each item with a positive value consumes a portion of any available space based on their `flex-grow` value.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we gave all of our items in the example above a `flex-grow` value of 1 then the available space in the flex container would be equally shared between our items and they would stretch to fill the container on the main axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Where the `flex-grow` property deals with adding space in the main axis, the `flex-shrink` property controls how it is taken away.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If we do not have enough space in the container to lay out our items, and `flex-shrink` is set to a positive integer, then the item can become smaller than the `flex-basis`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] As with `flex-grow`, different values can be assigned in order to cause one item to shrink faster than others ‚Äî an item with a higher value set for `flex-shrink` will shrink faster than its siblings that have lower values.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] An item can shrink down to its `min-content` size.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This minimum size is taken into account while working out the actual amount of shrinkage that will happen, which means that `flex-shrink` has the potential to appear less consistent than `flex-grow` in behavior.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] We'll therefore take a more detailed look at how this algorithm works in the article Controlling ratios of items along the main axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You will very rarely see the `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, and `flex-basis` properties used individually; instead they are combined into the `flex` shorthand.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `flex` shorthand allows you to set the three values in this order ‚Äî `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, `flex-basis`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The live sample below allows you to test out the different values of the flex shorthand; remember that the first value is `flex-grow`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Giving this a positive value means the item can grow.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The second is `flex-shrink` ‚Äî with a positive value the items can shrink, but only if their total values overflow the main axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The final value is `flex-basis`; this is the value the items are using as their base value to grow and shrink from.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] There are also some predefined shorthand values which cover most of the use cases.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You will often see these used in tutorials, and in many cases these are all you will need to use.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `initial` value is a CSS-wide keyword that represents the initial value for a property.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Setting `flex: initial` resets the item to the initial values of the three longhand properties, which is the same as `flex: 0 1 auto`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-grow` is `0`, so items will not grow larger than their `flex-basis` size.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-shrink` is `1`, so items can shrink if they need to rather than overflowing.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value of `flex-basis` is `auto`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Items will either use any size set on the item in the main dimension, or they will get their size from the content size.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `flex: auto` is the same as using `flex: 1 1 auto`; this is similar to `flex: initial`, except that the items can grow and fill the container as well as shrink if needed.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Using `flex: none` will create fully inflexible flex items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The items cannot grow or shrink and will be laid out using flexbox with a `flex-basis` of `auto`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The shorthand you often see in tutorials is `flex: 1` or `flex: 2` and so on.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This is the same as writing `flex: 1 1 0` or `flex: 2 1 0` and so on, respectively.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The items get minimum size due to `flex-basis: 0` and then proportionally grow to fill the available space.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In this case, the `flex-shrink` value of `1` is redundant because the items start with minimum size ‚Äî they're not given any size that could cause them to overflow the flex container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try these shorthand values in the live sample below.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] A key feature of flexbox is the ability to align and justify items on the main- and cross-axes, and to distribute space between flex items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Note that these properties are set on the flex container, not on the items themselves.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-items` property aligns all the flex items on the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value for this property is `stretch` and is why flex items stretch to the height of the flex container by default (or the width if `flex-direction` is set to `column` or `column-reverse`).
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] This height may come from the tallest item in the container or the size set on the flex container itself.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You could instead set `align-items` to `flex-start`, or simply `start`, in order to make the items line up at the start of the flex container, `flex-end`, or just `end`, to align them to the end, or `center` to align them in the center.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Try this in the live sample ‚Äî I have given the flex container a height in order that you can see how the items can be moved around inside the container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-items` is set on the flex container and impacts all the flex items.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If you want to align a flex item differently from others, you can set the `align-self` on the flex item.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `justify-content` property is used to align the items on the main axis, the direction in which `flex-direction` has set the flow.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The initial value is `flex-start` which will line the items up at the start edge of the container, but you could also set the value to `flex-end` to line them up at the end, or `center` to line them up in the center.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] You can also use the value `space-between` to take all the spare space after the items have been laid out, and share it out evenly between the items so there will be an equal amount of space between each item.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] To cause an equal amount of space on the right and left (or top and bottom for columns) of each item use the value `space-around`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With `space-around`, items have a half-size space on either end.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] Or, to cause items to have equal space around them use the value `space-evenly`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] With `space-evenly`, items have a full-size space on either end.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The article Aligning items in a flex container explores these properties in more depth, in order to have a better understanding of how they work.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] These basic examples, however, are useful in the majority of use cases.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `justify-items` property is ignored in flexbox layouts.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `place-items` property is a shorthand property for `align-items` and `justify-items`.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] If set on a flex container, it will set the alignment but not the justification, as `justify-items` is ignored in flexbox.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] There is another shorthand property, `place-content`, that defines the `align-content` and `justify-content` properties.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] The `align-content` property only affects flex containers that wrap, and is discussed in Aligning items in a flex container.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] After reading this article you should have an understanding of the basic features of flexbox.
[src:flexbox/basic-concepts-of-flexbox] In the next article, we will look at how this specification relates to other parts of CSS.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] It‚Äôs been available across browsers since September 2015.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The CSS **`align-items`** property sets the `align-self` value on all direct children as a group.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] In flexbox, it controls the alignment of items on the cross axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] In grid layout, it controls the alignment of items on the block axis within their grid areas.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The interactive example below uses grid layout to demonstrate some of the values of this property.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The flex items' margin boxes are centered within the line on the cross-axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] If the cross-size of an item is larger than the flex container, it will overflow equally in both directions.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The items are packed flush to each other toward the start edge of the alignment container in the appropriate axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The items are packed flush to each other toward the end edge of the alignment container in the appropriate axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The items are packed flush to the edge of the alignment container's start side of the item, in the appropriate axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The items are packed flush to the edge of the alignment container's end side of the item, in the appropriate axis.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] All flex items are aligned such that their flex container baselines align.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The item with the largest distance between its cross-start margin edge and its baseline is flushed with the cross-start edge of the line.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] If the item's cross-size is `auto`, the used size is set to the length necessary to be as close to filling the container as possible, respecting the item's width and height limits.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] If the item is not auto-sized, this value falls back to `flex-start`, and to `self-start` or `self-end` if the container's `align-content` is `first baseline` (or `baseline`) or `last baseline`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] In the case of anchor-positioned elements, aligns the items to the center of the associated anchor element in the block direction.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] See Centering on the anchor using `anchor-center`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] If the chosen keyword means that the item overflows the alignment container causing data loss, the item is instead aligned as if the alignment mode were `start`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] Regardless of the relative sizes of the item and alignment container and whether overflow which causes data loss might happen, the given alignment value is honored.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] Used in flex layout only, aligns the flex items flush against the flex container's main-start or cross-start side.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] When used outside of a flex formatting context, this value behaves as `start`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] Used in flex layout only, aligns the flex items flush against the flex container's main-end or cross-end side.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] When used outside of a flex formatting context, this value behaves as `end`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] In this example we have a container with six children.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] A `<select>` dropdown menu enables toggling the `display` of the container between `grid` and `flex`.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] A second menu enables changing the value of the container's `align-items` property.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] We style a the container and items in a manner that ensures we have two lines or rows or items.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] We defined `.flex` and `.grid` classes, which will be applied to the container with JavaScript.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] They set the `display` value of the container, and change its background and border colors providing an additional indicator that the layout has changed.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The six flex items each have a different background color, with the 4th item being two lines long and the 6th item having an enlarged font.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] We include a container `<div>` with six nested `<div>` children.
[src:flexbox/css-align-items] The HTML for the form and the JavaScript that changes the container's class have been hidden for the sake of brevity.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] The **`flex`** CSS shorthand property sets how a flex item will grow or shrink to fit the space available in its flex container.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] The `flex` property may be specified using one, two, or three values.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] Defines the `flex-grow` of the flex item.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] Defines the `flex-shrink` of the flex item.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] Defines the `flex-basis` of the flex item.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] The item is sized according to its `width` and `height` properties.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] It is fully inflexible: it neither shrinks nor grows in relation to the flex container.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] This is equivalent to setting `flex: 0 0 auto`.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] For most purposes, authors should set `flex` to one of the following values: `auto`, `initial`, `none`, or a positive unitless number.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] By default flex items don't shrink below their `min-content` size.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] To change this, set the item's `min-width` or `min-height`.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] This example shows how a flex item with `flex: auto` grows to absorb any free space in the container.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] The `#default` item takes up as much space as its width requires, but does not expand to take up any more space.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] All the remaining space is taken up by the `#flex-auto` item.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] When you click the `#flex-auto` item, we set the `#default` item's `display` property to `none`, removing it from the layout.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] The `#flex-auto` item then expands to occupy all the available space in the container.
[src:flexbox/css-flex] Clicking the `#flex-auto` item again adds the `#default` item back to the container.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] The **CSS flexible box layout** module defines a CSS box model optimized for user interface design, and the layout of items in one dimension.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] In the flex layout model, the children of a flex container can be laid out in any direction, and can "flex" their sizes, either growing to fill unused space or shrinking to avoid overflowing the parent.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Both horizontal and vertical alignment of the children can be easily manipulated.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] In the following example, a container has been set to `display: flex`, which means that the three child items become flex items.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] The value of `justify-content` has been set to `space-between` in order to space the items out evenly on the main axis.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] An equal amount of space is placed between each item with the left and right items being flush with the edges of the flex container.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] You can also see that the items are stretching on the cross axis, due to the default value of `align-items` being `stretch`.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] The items stretch to the height of the flex container, making them each appear as tall as the tallest item.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] How Flexbox relates to other layout methods and other CSS specifications.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] How the box alignment properties work with Flexbox.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Explaining the different ways to change the order and direction of items, and covering the potential issues in doing so.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Explaining the flex-grow, flex-shrink and flex-basis properties.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] How to create flex containers with multiple lines and control the display of the items in those lines.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Common design patterns that are typical Flexbox use cases.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Learn how to use flexbox layout to create web layouts.
[src:flexbox/css-flexible-box-layout] Details features of CSS box alignment which are specific to flexbox.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The CSS **`justify-content`** property defines how the browser distributes space between and around content items along the main axis of a flex container and the inline axis of grid and multicol containers.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The interactive example below demonstrates some `justify-content` values using grid layout.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the start edge of the alignment container in the main axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the end edge of the alignment container in the main axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the start edge of the alignment container on the flex container's main-start side.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] For items that are not children of a flex container, this value is treated like `start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other at the end edge of the alignment container on the flex container's main-end side.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] For items that are not children of a flex container, this value is treated like `end`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the center of the alignment container along the main axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the left edge of the alignment container.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] When the property's horizontal axis is not parallel with the inline axis, such as when `flex-direction: column;` is set, this value behaves like `start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are packed flush to each other toward the right edge of the alignment container in the appropriate axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] If the property's axis is not parallel with the inline axis (in a grid container) or the main-axis (in a flexbox container), this value behaves like `start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Behaves as `stretch`, except in the case of multi-column containers with a non-`auto` `column-width`, in which case the columns take their specified `column-width` rather than stretching to fill the container.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] As `stretch` behaves as `start` in flex containers, `normal` also behaves as `start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The items are evenly distributed within the alignment container along the main axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The spacing between each pair of adjacent items is the same.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The first item is flush with the main-start edge, and the last item is flush with the main-end edge.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The empty space before the first and after the last item equals half of the space between each pair of adjacent items.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] If there is only one item, it will be centered.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The spacing between each pair of adjacent items, the main-start edge and the first item, and the main-end edge and the last item, are all exactly the same.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] If the item overflows the alignment container, then the item is aligned as if the alignment mode is `start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The desired alignment will not be implemented.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Even if the item overflows the alignment container, the desired alignment will be implemented.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Unlike `safe`, which will ignore the desired alignment in favor of preventing overflow.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Defined in the CSS box alignment module, `justify-content` applies to multicol containers, flex containers, and grid containers.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The property does not apply to and has no effect on block containers.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] This property shares many keyword values with the `align-content` property, but not all!
[src:flexbox/justify-content] `justify-content` isn't involved in baseline alignment, and therefore does not take baseline values.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] In flex layouts, the property defines how positive free space is distributed between or around flex items along the main axis.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] This property impacts the space between elements in a line, not the space between lines.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The alignment is done after the lengths and auto margins are applied, which means that when one or more flex items in a line have a `flex-grow` factor greater than `0`, the property has no effect as there is no space to distribute along that line.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Also, as stretching along the main axis is controlled by `flex`, the `stretch` value behaves as `flex-start`.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] With grid layout, this property distributes available space between or around grid columns, not grid items.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] If the grid container is larger than the grid itself, the `justify-content` property can be used to justify the grid along the inline axis, aligning the grid columns.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Grid `auto` track sizes (and only `auto` track sizes) can be stretched by the `align-content` and `justify-content` properties.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Therefore by default, an `auto` sized track will take up any remaining space in the grid container.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] As the grid's inline size has to be less than the grid container's inline size for there to be space to distribute, the property has no effect in this case.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] In this example, we have a grid that is narrower than its grid container, and we use `justify-content` to distribute the available space evenly around and between the grid columns.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The `<section>` container, our grid container to-be, has 16 nested `<div>`s that will become grid items.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] We set the container width to `500px` and specify three columns, each `80px` wide, meaning there is `260px` of available space to distribute between or around them.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] We then set `justify-content: space-evenly`, which means there will be `65px` of space before, between, and after each column.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] We set different widths (and background colors) to demonstrate how the justification is applied to the columns.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Note that `justify-contents` aligns the columns and has no effect on the items or alignment in grid areas.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Grid items, even those that overflow their grid cell, do not impact column justification.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] This example demonstrates the `safe` keyterm.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] We specify four centered flex items that are not allowed to wrap, and as a result, overflow their single flex-line container.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] As an item overflows the alignment container, with `safe` included the alignment mode behaves as `start` and the `center` alignment is not implemented.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The `safe` keyterm has no effect if the items do not overflow the container.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] This example includes a multi-line wrapping flex layout.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] The second flex item has a positive flex growth factor, consuming all the available free space in the first flex line.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Select different keywords from the drop-down menu to visualize the different `justify-content` keyword values.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] Because an item on the first line can grow, there is no available space on that line for the `justify-content` property to distribute.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] With the `space-between` value, the first item on each line is flush with the main-start edge, and the last item is flush with the main-end edge.
[src:flexbox/justify-content] As a result, if a line has only one item, it will be aligned with the main-start edge (as seen in the last line).
[src:flexbox/justify-content] This is not the case for other `space-*` values, such as `space-evenly` and `space-around`, which center one-item flex-lines.
